                    <li class="comment even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-102">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-102" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-102">
                <span id="dsq-author-user-102">Helix</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-102" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-102" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>In the 90s  was the government on a net basis not accumulating cash and did we not have a super bull ? Where am I going wrong ? </p>
<p>Great site Thanks</p>
</div>
        </div>
    </li>

    <ul class="children">
    <li class="comment byuser comment-author-greshams-law-admin bypostauthor odd alt depth-2" id="dsq-comment-103">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-103" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-103">
http://greshams-law.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-103">Aftab Singh</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-103" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-103" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>Helix,</p>
<p>Indeed, during the 90s the government was on a trend of receiving more taxes than it spent. However, we should note that this was primarily a function of a private sector that was intent on levering up. Net savings by the private sector were progressively decreasing. That &#8211; I contend &#8211; was the important thing: A levering private sector is very bullish of asset prices.</p>
<p>Now, in contrast, the private sector has deleveraging tendencies &#8211; i.e. it is having to buy back the money it &#8216;sold short&#8217;. Nowadays, when the government spends in excess of what it brings in, that eases the deleveraging pressure &#8211; which can bring countertrend rallies. Likewise, if the government ceases to spend in excess of what it brings in, the private sector&#8217;s deleveraging pressure rises to its natural level &#8211; which can bring downward legs in asset markets.</p>
</div>
        </div>
    </li>

    </li><!-- #comment-## -->
</ul><!-- .children -->
