</li><!-- #comment-## -->
    <li class="comment byuser comment-author-greshams-law-admin bypostauthor even thread-even depth-1" id="dsq-comment-121">
        <div id="dsq-comment-header-121" class="dsq-comment-header">
            <cite id="dsq-cite-121">
http://greshams-law.com                <span id="dsq-author-user-121">Aftab Singh</span>
            </cite>
        </div>
        <div id="dsq-comment-body-121" class="dsq-comment-body">
            <div id="dsq-comment-message-121" class="dsq-comment-message"><p>I got a good question from a reader, so I thought I&#8217;d post my answer here incase anyone else is interested:</p>
<blockquote><p>I&#8217;m not sure the blog takes a clear position wrt to the impact of the<br />
USG paying back its debt. Would you consider that accumulation of currency?&#8221;</p></blockquote>
<p>Ah, I wouldn&#8217;t really say that the USG paying down debt is &#8216;accumulation of currency&#8217;. Rather, I&#8217;d say that they&#8217;re covering their shorts on money. That is, they&#8217;re &#8216;buying back&#8217; money (by selling things). I just say that &#8211; when they do this &#8211; they are joining the same side as the &#8216;private sector&#8217;. It seems that the private sector reached its maximum capacity for leverage in either 2000 or 2008, and now they&#8217;re &#8216;buying back&#8217; the money that they sold short. If the government were to &#8216;buy back&#8217; money at the same time, they would be making the short squeeze in money even more &#8216;squeezed&#8217;. The reason why I use the term &#8216;accumulation of currency&#8217; is to be exact when considering the daily treasury statement. The daily treasury statement shows how much money the Government has got in the bank. When they&#8217;re spending more than they&#8217;re receiving (including money from bond issues), I call that &#8216;withdrawing&#8217; and conversely when they&#8217;re spending less than they&#8217;re receiving, I call that &#8216;accumulating cash&#8217;. My rough estimate is that when the US Treasury are on a spending spree (i.e. selling cash for stuff), they alleviate the money &#8216;short squeeze&#8217; occurring in the private sector. That is to say, everyone in the private sector wants to sell stuff to buy money, and the government alleviates that pressure via buying stuff with money. My point is that, when the operating balance rises, they aren&#8217;t alleviating that pressure (to the same degree or at all) and so we can consider placing trades to comply with the long-term deleveraging pressure.</p>
</div>
        </div>
    </li>

